<subSubSection lastPageId="47" lastPageNumber="248" pageId="46" pageNumber="247" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="46.[151,1437,1883,2018]" pageId="46" pageNumber="247">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1884,1910]" pageId="46" pageNumber="247">DIAGNOSIS.</emphasis>
This species (
<figureCitation box="[431,563,1883,1910]" captionStart="FIGURES 55–66" captionStartId="35.[151,264,1793,1818]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1767]" captionTargetId="figure@35.[151,1436,181,1767]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURES 55–66. Nigrotomocoris and Schaffnerocoris spp. 55, N. nigrus (Carvalho), male (dorsal aspect). 56, N. nigrus, male (lateral aspect). 57, N. nigrus, female (dorsal aspect). 58, N. tibiopallidus (Carvalho), male (dorsal aspect). 59, N. tibiopallidus, male (lateral aspect). 60, N. tibiopallidus, female (dorsal aspect). 61, S. fuscotibialis, n. sp., male (dorsal aspect). 62, S. fuscotibialis, n. sp., male (lateral aspect). 63, S. pallipes, n. sp., male (dorsal aspect). 64, S. pallipes, n. sp., female (dorsal aspect). 65, S. similis, n. sp., male (dorsal aspect). 66, S. similis, n. sp., male (lateral aspect)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3816476" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3816476/files/figure.png" pageId="46" pageNumber="247">Figs. 63, 64</figureCitation>
) is distinguished by the pale to dark red hemelytra (with the costal margin pale on the darkest specimens), uniformly pale legs, and male genitalia, especially the large, stout genital tubercle (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 129–137" captionStartId="46.[151,264,1558,1583]" captionTargetBox="[231,1357,417,1532]" captionTargetId="figure@46.[230,1357,417,1533]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="FIGURES 129–137. Male genital tubercles of Laterospinocoris, Nigrotomocoris, and Schaffnerocoris spp. 129, L. cyaneipennis. 130, L. mexicanus, n. sp. 131, N. keltoni, n. sp. 132, N. longirostris, n. sp. 133, N. nigrus. 134, N. tibiopallidus. 135, S. fuscotibialis, n. sp. 136, S. pallipes, n. sp. 137, S. similis, n. sp." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3816494" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3816494/files/figure.png" pageId="46" pageNumber="247">Fig. 136</figureCitation>
), and weakly C-shaped, apically acute right paramere (
<figureCitation box="[813,910,1955,1982]" captionStart="FIGURES 113–118" captionStartId="41.[151,264,1368,1393]" captionTargetBox="[154,1432,313,1338]" captionTargetId="figure@41.[151,1436,308,1343]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIGURES 113–118. Male genitalia of Schaffnerocoris spp. S. fuscotibialis, n. sp.: 113, right paramere. 114, left paramere. S. pallipes, n. sp.: 115, left paramere. 116, right paramere. S. tibiopallidus, n. sp.: 117, left paramere. 118, right paramere." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3816486" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3816486/files/figure.png" pageId="46" pageNumber="247">Fig. 116</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="46.[151,1437,1883,2018]" lastBlockId="47.[151,1437,153,467]" lastPageId="47" lastPageNumber="248" pageId="46" pageNumber="247">
It is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Henry &amp; Menard" authorityYear="2020" box="[370,472,1991,2018]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Schaffnerocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="46" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="similis">
<emphasis box="[370,472,1991,2018]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="247">S. similis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in general color, including the pale legs, but differs in the male genitalia, especially the longer, stouter genital tubercle and the C-shaped rather than S-shaped right paramere. From 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Henry &amp; Menard" authorityYear="2020" box="[1223,1388,153,179]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Schaffnerocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuscotibialis">
<emphasis box="[1223,1388,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="248">S. fuscotibialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is distinguished by the uniformly pale legs and apically acute right paramere.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
